<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE LEGACY OF ART SEIDENBAUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Art Seidenbaum kick-started my writing career in Los Angeles eight years ago by 
assigning me book reviews (which he referred to as "chores"). At first I 
demurred, uncertain of being up to the task. 
</P>
<P>
But he bolstered my confidence, guiding me with his editing acumen, and on many 
occasions rescuing my writing from sure consignment to the dustbin with his 
suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
And he made an indelible impression. Whenever I self edit, I continually ask, 
"Would this pass muster with Art Seidenbaum?" The Irish have a phrase, "Ni bas 
acht a fas," which translated from the Gaelic means not dead but continuing to 
remain alive and, in fact, to grow in memory with time's passing. Every time I 
write something, Art Seidenbaum remains very much alive for me. 
</P>
<P>
TOM STAPLETON 
</P>
<P>
Glendale 
</P>
</TEXT>
